    <header class="header">
      <h1>Growing Peppers in Short Growing Seasons</h1>
      <p class="tagline">Peppers reward patience — but they need an early start.</p>
      <p class="lede">
        Peppers are slower than tomatoes in cool climates. In a short growing season,
        a strong indoor start and warm transplant conditions make the difference.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Indoor start:</strong> 8–10 weeks before your average last frost</li>
        <li><strong>Transplant:</strong> ~2–4 weeks after last frost (warm nights matter)</li>
        <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 65–95+ days depending on variety</li>
        <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> None (protect from all frost)</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        For exact windows based on your dates, use the
        <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Starting Planner</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Best Varieties for Short Seasons</h2>
      <p>
        Look for early-maturing varieties and smaller fruit types. In cool summers,
        large thick-walled peppers can finish late.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Early bell or “short-season” bell varieties</li>
        <li>Thin-walled frying peppers for faster ripening</li>
        <li>Hot peppers often finish more reliably than large bells</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="fine muted">
        Tip: seed packets vary. Use the listed days to maturity as a planning estimate, not a guarantee.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Common Short-Season Mistakes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Starting too late.</strong> Peppers don’t “catch up” easily once behind.</li>
        <li><strong>Transplanting into cold soil.</strong> Growth stalls hard in cool conditions.</li>
        <li><strong>Underheating seedlings.</strong> Warm germination and bright light prevent weak starts.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Fall Planning Notes</h2>
      <p>
        Peppers are frost sensitive, and ripening slows in late season. If frost risk is close,
        focus on fruit set and ripening rather than new flowers.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Remove late blossoms 4–6 weeks before first frost</li>
        <li>Use protection early in fall to extend ripening</li>
        <li>Harvest mature green fruit before frost if needed</li>
      </ul>
